{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πέπων</b>, ον, <br /> <i>genitive</i> ονος: <i>comparative</i> and <i>superlative</i> πεπαίτερος, -τατος:—properly of fruit, <b>cooked by the sun, ripe</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus “fragment” 34, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.23, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 181; ἄπιος 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 33.5 (_superlative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ὠμός, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 260, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 19.19 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of wine, <b>mellow</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 579, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πέπονα ποιεῖν τινα, by beating him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Comica Adespota” 125. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__b</b></Level4> of abscesses, <b>ripe, ready to suppurate</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hermippus Comicus 30. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> σίκυος π. a kind of <b>gourd</b> or <b>melon, not eaten till quite ripe</b> (whereas the σίκυος was eaten unripe), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ νούσων” 3.17, “Vict.” 2.55, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus Comedy texts 64.4, 4th c.BC: Anaxilas Comicus 36, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 926b4, Diocl.fragment 120 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πέπων alone distinguished from σίκυος, τοὺς σικύους καὶ τοὺς πέπονας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Num.11.5, compare 4th c.BC: Speusippus Philosophus cited in 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 2.68e, 4th-3rd c.BC: Phanias Historicus 34, 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 2.135, etc.: proverbial, μαλθακώτερος πέπονος σικύου 5th c.BC: Theopompus Comicus 72; ἀνὴρ ἐκεῖνος ἦν πεπαίτερος μόρων 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 264; π. ἀπίοιο 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 7.120. \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i>, as always in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus (more frequently in 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” than in 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey”), and in 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], in addressing a person, mostly as a term of endearment or familiarity, <b>kind, gentle</b>, πέπον Καπανηϊάδη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.109; Κύκνε πέπον 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 350 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὦ πέπον <b>good</b> brother!, <b>gentle</b> sir!, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.55, 9.252, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 544, 560, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κριὲ πέπον my <b>pet</b> ram (says Polyphemus), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.447: _comparative_, of a ἑταίρα, 4th c.BC: Xenarchus Comicus 4.9 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: in bad sense, ὦ πέπονες <b>ye weaklings!</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.235. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>mild, less acrid</b>, ῥεύματα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἀρχαίης ἰητρικῇς” 19 (_comparative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: hence <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>mild, gentle</b>, πεπαιτέρα γὰρ μοῖρα τῆς τυραννίδος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1365 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; μόχθος πέπων <b>softened</b> pain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 437, etc.: with _dative_, ἐχθροῖσι π\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. <b>gentle</b> to thy foes, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 66. (Cf. πέπειρος, πέσσω.) \">Refs 4th 